id: pm-bl8x
title: "ADR: workspace scale-out strategy — indexed reads, storage fan-out, and bounded-output contracts for 100k-1M-item workspaces (proposed)"
description: "Proposed ADR (open=proposed, close=accepted per pm-m2u1 convention) that fixes the ground rules for the scale-out initiative epic. Duplicate check 2026-07-06: searched scalability/sharding/index/pagination — no existing open or closed item covers workspace-scale architecture."
type: Decision
status: open
priority: 2
tags[5]: adr,architecture,"area:storage",performance,scale
created_at: "2026-07-06T21:23:34.365Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-11T10:38:42.910Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 480
acceptance_criteria: "ADR records the decision for: (1) persistent read-index format + invalidation, (2) item-directory fan-out scheme + format_version migration path, (3) bounded-output/cursor-pagination contract, (4) claim/lock scaling approach, (5) git-repo growth policy (packing, history compaction cadence); status accepted (item closed) before dependent implementation tasks start"
goal: project management = context management
objective: Fix the architectural rules that let pm stay sub-second and bounded-token as workspaces grow to 100k-1M items with thousands of concurrent agents
value: "Without a scale strategy decided up front, index/sharding/pagination work would be ad-hoc and could require repeated storage migrations"
why_now: Product goal explicitly targets workspaces of hundreds of thousands to millions of items with thousands of parallel agents; current read paths scan the full item directory and output is unbounded by default
parent: pm-m2u1
risk: high
confidence: medium
notes[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-10T21:41:16.024Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision-point-3 input (2026-07-10 planning pass): pm-dfg0 now carries a grounded S1-S4 scoping note with the verified current pagination surface (list --limit/--offset unbounded-by-default; search --limit only; context --depth full = MAX_SAFE_INTEGER hole; no cursor anywhere). Recommendation from that analysis: cursor tokens over offset (opaque stable-sort-tuple cursor, id tiebreak) — offset re-scans degrade at 100k+ and break under concurrent mutation; a threshold-gated default limit preserves small-workspace ergonomics (pm-z436). The S1 cursor primitive can be spiked in the pm-rjqr SDK query facade as ADR input before this ADR formally lands."
  "2026-07-11T10:38:42.909Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision inputs from the 2026-07-11 perf brainstorm (ledger on pm-9rxu):\n- Option 1 (read index) gains a maintenance-strategy sub-decision: incremental index updates riding the existing mutation path (same hook family as background semantic refresh — write-time O(1) upkeep) vs rebuild-on-stale-read. Invalidation source candidate: mtime/stat journal, same keying the shipped three-tier metadata cache (ADR pm-vnie) already trusts.\n- Any embedded store (SQLite/LanceDB-adjacent) stays a gitignored, rebuildable CACHE — never authoritative (ADR pm-i7i4). Rebuild cost at 1M items is itself a budgeted number (mi2x tier reports).\n- Startup is near-floor (bundle + lazy imports + compile cache + lazy activation all shipped), so this ADR's read-path options carry the remaining order-of-magnitude; git-subprocess count on read paths is a fifth decision driver worth stating explicitly (pure reads may need zero git spawns)."
body: "## Context\nEvery pm read command today enumerates .agents/pm/<type>/*.toon (O(workspace)); history is one JSONL stream per item; locks are per-item files; output size is unbounded by default. This is fine at 1.6k items and breaks down at 100k+.\n\n## Decision drivers\n- Context building must stay sub-second and bounded-token at 1M items (philosophy: project management = context management).\n- Thousands of agents mutate concurrently: index maintenance must be as safe as appendLineAtomic; no global write hotspots.\n- Git-native storage is a hard constraint: everything must remain diffable, mergeable, and recoverable from the working tree alone (index must be derivable/rebuildable, never authoritative).\n- Zero data-format breakage: fan-out/sharding ships behind format_version gating with a migration.\n\n## Options to evaluate (decision pending)\n1. Read index: single compact ledger file vs per-type index vs embedded (SQLite/LanceDB-adjacent) cache under .agents/pm/runtime (gitignored, rebuildable).\n2. Directory fan-out: hash-bucket subdirs per type vs date-bucketed vs flat-with-index-only.\n3. Pagination: cursor tokens (stable sort key) vs offset; default --limit for list/search/context at scale.\n4. Claim/lock scaling: per-item locks already shard naturally; singleton files (settings/session) need the pm-bgcu fix plus contention budget.\n5. Git growth: gc/history-compact cadence, git gc/packing guidance, optional archive tier for closed items."
